      "content": "## 2) SAR reasoning (why features affect CYP2D6 inhibition)\n- **CYP2D6 inhibitors commonly have a protonatable basic N** that can form a **salt bridge/ionic interaction** with the active-site acidic residue (often described as **Asp301** in CYP2D6), anchoring the ligand.\n- The molecule\u2019s **secondary amine** is positioned between aromatic systems (benzylamine-like), which often provides the right **basic center + hydrophobic bulk** arrangement to bind tightly.\n- The **multiple aromatic rings** increase **\u03c0\u2013\u03c0 / hydrophobic interactions** in the active site and generally increase affinity to CYP enzymes, including CYP2D6.\n- The **heteroaromatic nitrogens** can contribute additional **H-bonding / dipole interactions** and may tune the pKa of the system; even if they reduce basicity somewhat, the scaffold still likely presents at least one **protonated center** at pH 7.4.",
